<p>Mike Patey, the Utah entrepreneur who transformed his Polish-built Wilga 2000 short takeoff and landing (STOL) aircraft into a million-dollar "<a href="https://arstechnica.com/cars/2018/08/one-man-designed-and-built-the-ultimate-bush-plane/">ultimate bush plane</a>" called DRACO, crashed on takeoff leaving the Reno National Championship Air Races on Monday.</p>
<p>Patey was attempting to depart Reno (where DRACO had been featured in a static display) the day after the races were over, seeking to beat a fast-moving weather front. With him aboard DRACO were his wife and best friend. All three escaped the crash without injury.</p>
<h2>The incident</h2>
<p>The crash occurred at about 10:12 pm local time. According to the Meteorological Aerodrome Report (METAR), the winds at Stead Airport were out of the southwest, blowing steady at 24 knots (28mph, or about 45km/h) and gusting to 38 knots (44mph, or about 71km/h). Patey was taking off on runway 26 with a crosswind from his left.</p>
