<figure class="intro-image intro-left"><img src="https://cdn.arstechnica.net/wp-content/uploads/2017/11/att-logo-800x494.jpg" alt="An AT&amp;T logo on a wall."><p class="caption" style="font-size:0.8em"><a href="https://cdn.arstechnica.net/wp-content/uploads/2017/11/att-logo.jpg" class="enlarge-link" data-height="1264" data-width="2048">Enlarge</a> <span class="sep">/</span> AT&amp;T logo. (credit: <a rel="nofollow" class="caption-link" href="https://www.flickr.com/photos/jeepersmedia/16162680598/in/photolist-qCeXQS-r7gGPW-Ge1BDj-FrHtsq-paKpAu-nNfZzT-opDwpK-p9vX7i-p9fr9P-oqz8aS-oqz7QU-o8R3QG-oqp6W9-qUJUeo-pXPivs-qCn9Dx-oS1EUg-oS2LwV-qCeXDE-k9FMRe-qUEsUT-qCeXzm-qCeXhN-ApqHRG-qS94Zc-r9q41z-r9tGeh-o6ovbz-pbveRk-AL8A9Z-nSwcQZ-qS19zy-qcy8jS-nL2oCS-nL2As1-o3pXH3-osAZTR-nnaNSV-o1tsDC-qS19DS-nL2AWC-nvKYzz-nfapcD-pe93u6-nN6nEw-kTzD5T-nDEx3F-nvLvxY-kTzDBz-nN6gRs">Mike Mozart / Flickr</a>)</p>  </figure><div><a name="page-1"></a></div>
<p>AT&amp;T supervisors encouraged sales reps to create fake DirecTV Now accounts to make the online video service seem more successful than it really was, a class-action complaint alleges.</p>
<p>AT&amp;T "promot[ed] and reward[ed] account fraud" such as creating the fake accounts and signing AT&amp;T customers up for DirecTV Now "without the customer knowing," the lawsuit claims.</p>
<p>The new allegations were made Friday in an <a href="https://www.courtlistener.com/recap/gov.uscourts.nysd.512865/gov.uscourts.nysd.512865.76.0_1.pdf">amended complaint</a> as part of a lawsuit filed against AT&amp;T in April in US District Court for the Southern District of New York. The lawsuit alleges that AT&amp;T lied to investors in order to hide DirecTV Now's failure.</p>
