<figure class="intro-image intro-left"><img src="https://cdn.arstechnica.net/wp-content/uploads/2019/09/GettyImages-473688628-800x533.jpg" alt="Richard Stallman"><p class="caption" style="font-size:0.8em"><a href="https://cdn.arstechnica.net/wp-content/uploads/2019/09/GettyImages-473688628.jpg" class="enlarge-link" data-height="3333" data-width="5000">Enlarge</a> <span class="sep">/</span> Richard Stallman in 2015. (credit: Michael Debets/Pacific Press/LightRocket via Getty Images)</p>  </figure><div><a name="page-1"></a></div>
<p>Free software pioneer Richard Stallman has resigned from his posts at MIT and the Free Software Foundation after leaked emails showed him quibbling over the definition of rape in a conversation related to Jeffrey Epstein.</p>
<p>The conversation that triggered Stallman's fall started when someone—names other than Stallman's are redacted in the <a href="https://www.vice.com/en_us/article/9ke3ke/famed-computer-scientist-richard-stallman-described-epstein-victims-as-entirely-willing">leaked emails</a>—posted about a planned protest at MIT. The email stated that famed MIT computer scientist Marvin Minsky "is accused of assaulting one of Epstein's victims."</p>
<p>Stallman objected, saying that the blurb "does an injustice" to Minsky because even if it's true that the then-17-year-old had sex with Minsky, "the most plausible scenario is that she presented herself to him as entirely willing." (One witness to the alleged incident <a href="https://pjmedia.com/instapundit/339725/">says</a> that Minsky, who died in 2016, declined to have sex with her.)</p>
